Skip to content Open Menu White House Logo Copy URL to your clipboard Share Economy National Security Budget Immigration Coronavirus.gov Search WhiteHouse.gov Open Search Social Programs America has spent more than $13 trillion on anti-poverty programs since the War on Poverty took off in 1965. While the number of seniors living in need today has declined, poverty for working-age Americans remains stagnant. Reforms that empower people by getting more citizens back to work will make our safety net stronger, and preserving programs for those truly in need will make these services more affordable for our fellow Americans. Remarks Remarks by President Trump at the White House Summit on Child Care and Paid Leave Social Programs Dec 12, 2019 Remarks Remarks by President Trump at Signing of Executive Order Establishing a White House Council on Eliminating Regulatory Barriers to Affordable Housing Social Programs Jun 25, 2019 Proclamations Proclamation on National Foster Care Month, 2019 Social Programs Apr 30, 2019 Proclamations Proclamation on National Volunteer Week, 2019 Social Programs Apr 5, 2019 Statements & Releases Global Athletic Community Calls for Reform of World Anti-Doping Agency Social Programs Oct 31, 2018 Proclamations Presidential Proclamation on National School Lunch Week, 2018 Social Programs Oct 12, 2018 Proclamations President Donald J. Trump Proclaims May 6 through May 12, 2018, as National Charter Schools Week Social Programs May 4, 2018 Proclamations President Donald J. Trump Proclaims May 2018 as National Foster Care Month Social Programs Apr 30, 2018 News Clips Secretary Carson: “Unlocking America’s Full Potential” Social Programs Apr 23, 2018 Social Programs Trump Is Reducing Poverty and Promoting Opportunity By: Sonny Perdue Apr 20, 2018 Previous 1 2 3 Next The White House Live Jobs Get Involved Copyright Policy Privacy Policy Twitter Facebook Instagram Contact News Remarks Briefings & Statements Presidential Actions Articles All News Issues Edu